[[File:RA-Ebisu.jpg|thumb|Statue of [[Ebisu (mythology)|Ebisu]], the god of fishermen and working men, in [[Tsu, Mie]]]]
'''Shinto''' is frequently a theme in [[Japanese popular culture]], including [[Cinema of Japan|film]], [[manga]], [[anime]], and video games. [[Shinto]] religion is at the core of Japanese culture and history and as such greatly affects the outcome of pop culture in modern Japan. The references are pervasive and have significant relevance to modern life in Japan amongst the new generations.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}

This page follows discussion of each genre with a list of works in Japanese or international popular culture that borrow significantly from Shinto myths, [[List of Japanese deities|deities]], and beliefs. It is not an exhaustive list of the many games, movies, manga and other cultural products that mention the religion or the names of its deities.

==Shinto as popular culture==
Shinto itself features in popular culture as folk Shinto or ''Minkan Shinto''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Picken|first1=Stuart D.B.|title=Historical Dictionary of Shinto|date=2011|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishing Group|location=Lanham|isbn=0810873729|edition=2nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xlG3F6gSm9UC|accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2017}}

==Anime and manga==
Shinto [[motif (narrative)|motifs]] and themes such as ''[[kami]]'' (gods or spirits) are particularly present in [[anime]] and [[manga]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cavallaro|first1=Dani|title=Magic as Metaphor in Anime: A Critical Study|date=2010|publisher=McFarland & Company|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=0786456205|page=8|quote=While in the Judaeo-Christian creed, the divinity is thought of as external to both time and space, in Shinto, spiritual forces (kami) are ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Steiff|first1=Josef|last2=Tamplin|first2=Tristan D.|title=Anime and Philosophy: Wide Eyed Wonder|date=2010|publisher=Open Court|location=Chicago, Illinos|isbn=0812696700|quote=For those of us not familiar with Shinto, its difficult to come to terms with a spiritual belief system that is not quite a religion and not ... Whether we comprehend the complex aspects of Shinto and its many evolutions‚Äîfrom its earliest origins to its ...}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2017}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hu|first1=Tze-yue G.|title=Frames of Anime: Culture and Image-Building|date=2010|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|location=Hong Kong|isbn=9622090982|page=48|quote=Shint≈ç scholar Muraoka Tsunetsugu identifies the creative musubi kami with "the power of growth and reproduction}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gymnich|first1=Marion|last2=Lichterfeld|first2=Imke|title=A Hundred Years of the Secret Garden: Frances Hodgson Burnett's Children's Classic Revisited|date=2012|publisher=Bonn University Press|location=G√∂ttingen|isbn=3847100548|page=111|quote=Shinto basically provides thousands of stories and ancient myths which Japanese become familiar with from an early age.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Napier|first1=Susan J.|title=Anime from Akira to Princess Mononoke: Experiencing Contemporary Japanese Animation|date=2001|publisher=Palgrave|location=New York|isbn=0312238630|page=113|edition=1st|quote=The film's haunting theme song is also clearly inspired by Shinto liturgy, 15 in its invocation to the gods to come and dance ... In fact, Oshii states that the "net" can be equated with the myriad gods of the Shinto religion,16 underlining the notion ...}}</ref>

*In ''[[Dream Saga]]'', the Earth is destroyed and recreated whenever humans have polluted it. This is done when [[Susanoo]], the shinto god of the sea and storms, (the brother to [[Amaterasu]]) consumes Amaterasu, the sun goddess. The two main characters, Yuuki and Takaomi, are given key roles in the process.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tachikawa|first1=Megumi|title=Dream Saga, Volume 3|date=2004|publisher=Tokyopop|location=Los Angeles, California|isbn=1591827760}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=February 2013}}
*In the manga ''[[Urusei Yatsura]]'', a parody of the famous story of Amaterasu hiding in [[Ama-no-Iwato]] cave is performed, which ends when the gods decide they enjoy the burlesque spectacle outside the cave so much, they lock Amaterasu inside.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}
*''Susanoo the Brawler'' is an episodic comic by Elizabeth Watasin, appearing in [[Action Girl Comics]], in which many members of the Japanese pantheon are incarnated as teenage girls.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}
*In the manga and anime series, ''[[Naruto]]'' there is a list of Mangekyo Sharingan Jutsus named [[Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto|Tsukuyomi]] (illusions created when the victim stares upon the Sharingan user), [[Amaterasu]] (inextinguishable flame), [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]] (a humanoid armor),  [[Izanagi]] (resetting ability) and [[Izanami-no-Mikoto|Izanami]] (looping ability).{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}

==Film==
Some Japanese films feature themes from Shinto religion or characters based on ''kami''.<ref name="Mazur">{{cite book|last1=Mazur|first1=Eric Michael|title=Encyclopedia of Religion and Film|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=9780313013980|page=250|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JPNfox6H5qwC&pg=PA250|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> This is especially the case in animated films, such as [[Hayao Miyazaki|Hayao Miyazaki's]] ''[[Princess Mononoke]]'' or ''[[Spirited Away]]'',<ref name="Mazur"/> but can also be seen in live action  and ''[[tokusatsu]]'' (special-effects driven) films.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}

*In the 2003 film ''[[Onmyoji (film)|Onmyoji II]]'', the story of Amaterasu (played by [[Ky≈çko Fukada]]) is revisited when the main character, based on [[Abe no Seimei]] (played by [[Mansai Nomura]]), assumes the role of the dancer in bringing the goddess back to earth. Susanoo is also a character in the film, played by [[Hayato Ichihara]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}
*In the ''[[Stargate]]'' series, Amaterasu is a Goa'uld System Lord who comes to Earth with Lord Yu and Camulus to form a temporary truce between Earth and the Goa'uld.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitt|first1=David|last2=Perlich|first2=John|title=Sith, Slayers, Stargates & Cyborgs: Modern Mythology in the New Millennium|date=2008|publisher=P. Lang|location=New York|isbn=9781433100956|page=88|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXbn5IenBgkC&pg=PA88|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref>
*In ''[[The Birth of Japan|The Three Treasures]]'' [[Toshir≈ç Mifune]] portrays Susanoo.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}
*In ''[[Wanpaku Ouji no Orochi Taiji|Little Prince and the Eight-Headed Dragon]]'' Susanoo wishes to follow his mother, [[Izanami]], to heaven when she dies, but his father, [[Izanagi]], tells him he cannot.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pitts|first1=Michael R.|title=Columbia Pictures: Horror, Science Fiction and Fantasy Films, 1928-1982|date=2010|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=9780786444472|page=134|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PKxN1as8XOMC&pg=PA134|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref>

==Video games==
{{Main article|Religion and video games}}
Video games may relate to themes or characters from Shinto, as well as [[Buddhism]], [[Christianity]], and other religions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perron|first1=Bernard|title=Horror Video Games: Essays on the Fusion of Fear and Play|date=2009|publisher=McFarland & Company|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|isbn=9780786441976|pages=95-120|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pNaQLQC9XhEC&pg=PA95|accessdate=2 February 2013}}</ref><ref name="Ong">{{Cite web |title=The Religions Behind Final Fantasy|last=Ong|first=Alicia|url=http://www.stanford.edu/group/htgg/sts145papers/aong_2001_2.pdf|accessdate=2012-02-02}}</ref> Such games may present a [[Heterodoxy|heterodox]] or alternative take on religion, or even [[parody]] traditional practice or belief.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Bainbridge|first1=William Sims |last2=Bainbridge|first2=Wilma Alice|title=Electronic game research methodologies: Studying religious implications|journal=Review of Religious Research|volume=49|issue=1|year=2007|pages=35‚Äì53}}</ref> In addition to Shinto stories or ''kami'', themes such as the sacredness of nature or the place of magic in everyday life are also visible in such games.<ref name="Ong"/>
*In the 2006 video game ''[[≈åkami]]'', Amaterasu is depicted as a white wolf and she is [[Amaterasu (≈åkami)|the main protagonist of the game]]. As in the traditional Shinto, Amaterasu is the goddess of the sun, but in the game she controls many other powers as well by painting things.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Walsh|first1=Doug|title=≈åkami: Official Strategy Guide for Nintendo Wii|date=2008|publisher=Brady Games|location=Indianapolis, Indiana|isbn=9780744010350|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BL0vMAAACAAJ}}</ref> This depiction of Amaterasu is also a playable character in ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom 3: Fate of Two Worlds]]'' and ''[[Ultimate Marvel vs. Capcom 3]]''.
*The ''[[Shin Megami Tensei]]'' Series have several references to Shinto and religion in general. Starting from a name that translates as True Goddess Reincarnation, to god Kagutsuchi in ''[[Shin Megami Tensei: Nocturne]]''.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}
*In 2016, four Japanese deities were included as playable characters in the [[multiplayer online battle arena]] video game ''[[Smite (video game)|Smite]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thursen|first1=Chris|title=Smite season 3: Japanese gods herald huge changes|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/smite-season-3-japanese-gods-herald-huge-changes|website=PC Gamer|accessdate=25 July 2017|language=en|date=7 January 2016}}</ref>
*In the video game ''[[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]]'', the Susanoo Fusion Rifle made an appearance as a Warlock exclusive weapon with the release of [[The Taken King]] expansion. The flavor text for this gun reads "The fearsome Storms of Today become the healing waters of tomorrow". This gun came out with the Stormcaller class, alluding to Susanoo's status as a storm deity.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}
*In the MMORPG ''[[Final Fantasy XIV]]'', Susanoo appears as a primal boss fight in the most recent expansion, Stormblood, as the first primal that the player faces in the story.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}

==Other works of popular culture==
Shinto stories or ''kami'' also appear in other works of popular culture, including work set in Japan but produced outside of the country.
*The Shinto deities Izanami and Izanagi (the latter incorrectly spelled as "Izaghi") appear in [[Puccini]]'s opera ''[[Madama Butterfly]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fisher|first1=Burton D.|title=Puccini's Madam Butterfly: Opera Classics Library Series|date=2001|publisher=Opera Journeys Publishing|location=Miami|isbn=9780977132034|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wDcU22Jb7PMC|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2017}}
*The Shinto deities Izanami and Izanagi (spelled "Izanaki") appear in [[Natsuo Kirino]]'s ''The Goddess Chronicle''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirino|first1=Natsuo|title=The Goddess Chronicle|date=2012|publisher=Canongate|location=Edinburgh; New York|isbn=9780802121097}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=June 2014}}
*In the novel, ''[[Giles Goat-Boy]]'', author [[John Barth]] makes reference to the people of Japan as the "Amaterasu," who were EATEN by WESCAC (a reference to the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki) during the "Second Campus Riot" (World War II).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Barth|first1=John|title=Giles Goat-Boy, or, The Revised New Syllabus|date=1987|publisher=Anchor Books/Doubleday|location=Garden City, New York|isbn=0385240864|edition=Anchor Books}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=June 2015}}{{Page needed|date=July 2017}}
*Izanagi and Izanami appear as minor supporting characters in the ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles Adventures]]'' comic book series, aiding the Turtles and their allies in battle against a powerful demon whose emergence from a damaged nuclear reactor threatens the safety of all Japan.<ref>''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles Adventures'' #28: "Midnight Sun", Part 1 (January 1992)</ref><ref>''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles Adventures'' #30: "Midnight Sun", Part 3 (March 1992)</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2018}}

